item.description: To all of my internet lady buddies on OnlyFans: Sheesh. I‚Äôm sorry. Scary, unfair, and bloody frustrating to have the rug pulled out from under you like that. Creating original content, no matter what it is, is complex: it‚Äôs time-consuming, emotionally taxing, and pushes your creativity to the limits; it‚Äôs also liberating ‚Äî not just because you‚Äôre paying the bills on your own terms, but because when you hit the publish button, you‚Äôre putting a bit of your soul out there into the world. There‚Äôs an art to it. Lighting, angles, pixels, cleverness, gumption, vulnerability. I haven‚Äôt used the platform myself. But as someone generally opposed to censorship, the principle bugs me. Short-sighted puritanical legislation (which never keeps up with technology in the first place); credit card companies dictating spending habits; penny-pinching corporate chicanery; the general short stick perpetually extended to those in the world‚Äôs oldest profession... It just sucks. So, listen‚Ä¶ I know it‚Äôs not much, but I‚Äôve been on Patreon for a few years now. If you haven‚Äôt tried it, it‚Äôs a really solid platform. They don‚Äôt allow explicit material (never have), but they do give a lot of leeway to content that‚Äôs simply ‚Äúmature.‚Äù (Think Playboy levels ‚Äî titillating, but with some classy substance [one would hope!].) Plus, they pay when they‚Äôre say they‚Äôre going to, and their customer service is swell. I know for a fact that some of you are thinking of opening shop on Patreon. I‚Äôm sure that a lot more of you have been tossing the idea around as well. If you are, I would be more than happy to share my experiences, along with a few tips, tricks, and observations for getting established there. I actually have a bit of an essay that I put together; if you‚Äôd like me to forward you a copy, for whatever it‚Äôs worth, I would be pleased to. DM me your email address, and I‚Äôll shoot it along. üôÇ In the meantime, take care. I know this is the least ideal time to have to worry about your livelihood. I‚Äôve been there. It sucks.
